  "prompt": "After demonetization of Rs.500 and Rs.1000 notes, what will happen to old notes?",
  "response": "After the demonetization of Rs.500 and Rs.1000 notes in India in 2016, the old notes were essentially rendered invalid as legal tender. However, the government and the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) put in place certain measures to handle the situation:\n\n1. **Exchange Period**: Initially, a limited period was given during which people could exchange their old notes for new ones at banks. The deadline for this was extended several times to accommodate the public.\n\n2. **Deposit into Bank Accounts**: People were allowed to deposit the old notes into their bank accounts, subject to certain conditions and scrutiny to prevent money laundering.\n\n3. **Destruction**: After the exchange and deposit period ended, the old notes were collected and destroyed by the RBI to prevent their re-entry into the economy.\n\n4. **Numismatic Value**: Some of the old notes were retained for their numismatic value and as historical artifacts.\n\n5. **Special Cases**: For Indians abroad and in special circumstances, arrangements were made to exchange the old notes through Indian embassies and consulates.\n\nIn summary, the old Rs.500 and Rs.1000 notes were phased out of circulation, exchanged or deposited during a specified period, and then destroyed, with a few being preserved for historical and numismatic purposes.",
